11 (f) "Sex" means the organization of body parts and gametes for reproduction in human beings and
12 other organisms. In human beings, there are exactly two sexes, male and female, with two corresponding types
13 of gametes. The sexes are determined by the biological and genetic indication of male or female, including sex
14 chromosomes, naturally occurring sex chromosomes, gonads, and nonambiguous internal and external
15 genitalia present at birth, without regard to an individual's psychological, behavioral, social, cultural, chosen, or
16 subjective experience of gender whether someone is male or female, which is distinguished based on the type
17 of gamete, sperm or eggs, they are capable of or expected to produce, as dictated by their primary sexual
18 anatomy. Because there are only two types of gametes, sperm and ova, with two corresponding reproductive
19 systems, there are only two sexes: male and female. An individual’s sex is rooted in reproductive anatomy and
20 is in no way influenced or defined by one’s psychological state, behavior, expression, or personal identity.
